## How Tokens Work — Access Token vs Refresh Token

```
User signs in
    ↓
Supabase issues TWO tokens:

1. ACCESS TOKEN (JWT)
   - Short-lived (1 hour default, configurable)
   - Contains user id, email, role, custom claims
   - Sent with every API request as Bearer token
   - CANNOT be revoked before expiry (this is a hard limit of JWT design)
   - Validated locally (no network call needed)

2. REFRESH TOKEN
   - Long-lived (never expires by default unless session controls set)
   - Single-use — exchanged for a new access token when access token expires
   - Stored in httpOnly cookie by @supabase/ssr
   - CAN be revoked (signOut() invalidates it)
   - Requires a network call to exchange
```

### Why you cannot instantly lock out a user

```typescript
// You ban a user in the database
await adminSupabase.auth.admin.updateUserById(userId, { banned: true })

// Problem: their ACCESS TOKEN is still valid for up to 1 hour
// They can still make API requests until the token expires

// Fix: set a short JWT expiry for security-critical apps
// Dashboard → Auth → JWT expiry → set to 300 (5 minutes)
// Trade-off: more frequent refresh token exchanges (performance cost)

// Immediate lockout: set expiry to 300s AND ban at the RLS level:
CREATE POLICY "block_banned" ON sensitive_table FOR ALL
USING (
  NOT EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM public.banned_users WHERE user_id = auth.uid()
  )
);
// RLS is checked on every query — instant effect
```

