## PKCE Flow — Why OAuth Requires a Callback Route

`@supabase/ssr` uses PKCE (Proof Key for Code Exchange) by default — the secure OAuth standard. After the OAuth redirect, you MUST complete the exchange in a callback route.

```typescript
// app/auth/callback/route.ts — REQUIRED for all OAuth and magic links
import { createClient } from '@/lib/supabase/server'
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server'

export async function GET(request: NextRequest) {
  const { searchParams, origin } = new URL(request.url)
  const code = searchParams.get('code')
  const next = searchParams.get('next') ?? '/'

  if (code) {
    const supabase = await createClient()
    const { error } = await supabase.auth.exchangeCodeForSession(code)
    if (!error) {
      return NextResponse.redirect(`${origin}${next}`)
    }
  }

  // Auth failed — redirect to error page
  return NextResponse.redirect(`${origin}/auth/auth-code-error`)
}
```

```
This route must be registered as a redirect URL in:
Supabase Dashboard → Auth → URL Configuration → Redirect URLs
Add: https://yourdomain.com/auth/callback
Add: http://localhost:3000/auth/callback
```

```typescript
// OAuth sign-in — points to the callback route
const { error } = await supabase.auth.signInWithOAuth({
  provider: 'google',
  options: {
    redirectTo: `${window.location.origin}/auth/callback`,
  },
})
```

