## ISR / Cache Session Leak — CRITICAL SECURITY WARNING

```
Supabase official warning (2025):
If a Next.js route is cached (ISR, static generation, or route-level caching)
AND that route triggers a session refresh via middleware,
the Set-Cookie header containing the session tokens can be cached
and served to a different user.

Result: User A's authenticated session is served to User B.
This is a data breach.
```

```typescript
// DANGEROUS — do not cache authenticated routes
export const revalidate = 60  // ← NEVER use on authenticated routes

// DANGEROUS — do not use fetch with cache on auth-dependent routes
const data = await fetch(url, { next: { revalidate: 60 } })  // ← DANGEROUS if authed

// SAFE — force dynamic rendering for all authenticated pages
export const dynamic = 'force-dynamic'
// Add this to every layout.tsx and page.tsx inside /(protected)

// SAFE — or set in next.config.ts for entire app:
// experimental: { staleTimes: { dynamic: 0 } }
```

```typescript
// Also: Vercel fluid compute module-scope leak
// Do NOT store user data in module-level variables
let cachedUser: User | null = null  // ← DANGEROUS in serverless/edge

// SAFE — always get user from request context
export async function GET() {
  const supabase = await createClient()  // fresh client per request
  const { data: { user } } = await supabase.auth.getUser()  // per-request
}
```

